  "text": "## RBAC Verb Coverage Audit Summary\n\nThis audit identifies all Go source files that define the set of allowed RBAC verbs (get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete, deletecollection) and validates that API handlers enforce these verb constraints in Kubernetes v1.32.0.\n\n### Key Findings\n\n#### 1. **Verb Definition and Constants**\n\nThe standard Kubernetes RBAC verbs are defined in multiple locations:\n\n- **`pkg/apis/rbac/types.go` (internal) and `staging/src/k8s.io/api/rbac/v1/types.go`**: Define the `PolicyRule` struct with a `Verbs []string` field and constants `VerbAll = \"*\"`, `APIGroupAll = \"*\"`, `ResourceAll = \"*\"`\n\n- **`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/endpoints/installer.go` (line 177-189)**: Contains the critical `toDiscoveryKubeVerb` map that establishes the canonical verb mapping:\n  - `\"GET\"` → `\"get\"`\n  - `\"LIST\"` → `\"list\"`\n  - `\"WATCH\"` → `\"watch\"`\n  - `\"POST\"` → `\"create\"`\n  - `\"PUT\"` → `\"update\"`\n  - `\"PATCH\"` → `\"patch\"`\n  - `\"DELETE\"` → `\"delete\"`\n  - `\"DELETECOLLECTION\"` → `\"deletecollection\"`\n  - `\"CONNECT\"`, `\"PROXY\"`, `\"WATCHLIST\"` → additional non-standard verbs\n\n- **`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/endpoints/request/requestinfo.go`**: Defines `verbsWithSelectors = sets.NewString(\"list\", \"watch\", \"deletecollection\")` for verbs that support label/field selectors\n\n- **`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/endpoints/openapi/openapi.go`**: Defines a trie with all recognized verbs including: get, log, read, replace, patch, delete, deletecollection, watch, connect, proxy, list, create\n\n#### 2. **Verb Enforcement in API Handlers**\n\nAPI handlers enforce verb constraints through:\n\n- **`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/endpoints/installer.go`**: The `APIInstaller.registerResourceHandlers()` function (lines 284-1127) dynamically determines which verbs are supported by checking if storage objects implement specific interfaces:\n  - `rest.Creater` → supports \"create\" (POST)\n  - `rest.Lister` → supports \"list\" (GET on collection)\n  - `rest.Getter` → supports \"get\" (GET on item)\n  - `rest.Updater` → supports \"update\" (PUT)\n  - `rest.Patcher` → supports \"patch\" (PATCH)\n  - `rest.GracefulDeleter` → supports \"delete\" (DELETE)\n  - `rest.CollectionDeleter` → supports \"deletecollection\" (DELETE on collection)\n  - `rest.Watcher` → supports \"watch\"\n  - `rest.Connecter` → supports \"connect\"\n\n#### 3. **Verb Validation in RBAC Rules**\n\nVerb validation occurs at multiple levels:\n\n- **`pkg/apis/rbac/helpers.go` (lines 169-207)**: The `PolicyRuleBuilder.Rule()` method in the internal RBAC package validates that certain verbs cannot be used with ResourceNames:\n  ```\n  case \"list\", \"watch\", \"create\", \"deletecollection\":\n      // These verbs cannot be used when ResourceNames are specified\n  ```\n\n- **`pkg/apis/rbac/v1/helpers.go` (lines 72-100)**: The v1 `PolicyRuleBuilder.Rule()` method does **NOT** include the ResourceNames validation present in the internal version. This is a notable gap in verb constraint enforcement.\n\n- **`pkg/apis/rbac/validation/validation.go`**: The `ValidatePolicyRule()` function validates that:\n  - Verbs list is not empty (line 105-107)\n  - Rules properly specify either resources or nonResourceURLs\n  - Non-resource rules cannot also have apiGroups, resources, or resourceNames\n  - However, it does NOT validate that verbs come from an approved list\n\n#### 4. **Verb Matching and Authorization**\n\nWhen authorizing requests:\n\n- **`pkg/apis/rbac/v1/evaluation_helpers.go`**: The `VerbMatches()` function (lines 26-37) checks if a requested verb matches the verbs in a PolicyRule. It supports the wildcard verb `\"*\"` for matching all verbs.\n\n- **`plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/rbac.go`**: The `RuleAllows()` function (lines 178-193) uses `VerbMatches()` to check if a PolicyRule authorizes a specific verb request.\n\n- **`pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go`**: The `ConfirmNoEscalation()` function uses RBAC rules to prevent privilege escalation by verifying that users cannot grant permissions they don't already have.\n\n### Critical Gap: Incomplete Verb Validation\n\n**Issue**: While the system enforces certain constraints (e.g., list/watch/create/deletecollection cannot be used with ResourceNames), there is **no comprehensive validation** that RBAC PolicyRule verbs are limited to the standard Kubernetes verb set. The API validation layer (`ValidatePolicyRule`) only checks that the `Verbs` field is non-empty—it does not validate that verbs come from the approved set.\n\n**Evidence**: \n- `pkg/apis/rbac/validation/validation.go` line 105-107 only checks `len(rule.Verbs) == 0`\n- There is no cross-reference to `toDiscoveryKubeVerb` or a similar validation constant during rule creation\n- This means a user could theoretically create a PolicyRule with verbs like `[\"admin\", \"superuser\"]` and it would pass validation\n\n### Additional Discrepancy\n\nThe v1 and internal RBAC helpers have diverged:\n- **`pkg/apis/rbac/helpers.go`** includes verb constraint validation (lines 189-200)\n- **`pkg/apis/rbac/v1/helpers.go`** is missing this validation entirely\n\nThis creates an inconsistency where internal API usage enforces stricter constraints than external v1 API usage.\n"
}

